<h1>nan</h1>
<p><strong>nan</strong> is a <a href="../xx/subordinatingConjunctions.php">subordinating conjunction</a>, typically governing a <a href="../xx/tense.php">conditional</a> <a href="../xx/dependency.php">dependent</a> verb form, and usually modifying a conditional tense verb form or particle.</p>
<p><strong>nan</strong> generally corresponds to past-conditional uses of the English word <a href="../../en/if.php"><em>if</em></a>, and complements the other Gaelic conditional-hypothetical subordinating conjunctions <a href="ma.php"><strong>ma</strong></a> and <a href="mura.php"><strong>mura</strong></a>.</p>
<p><strong>nan</strong> is written as <strong>nam</strong> when the following word starts with a labial consonant <strong>b-</strong>, <strong>p-</strong>, <strong>f-</strong>, <strong>m-</strong>.</p>
<hr/>
<p>Here are some canonical corpus examples from reported speech:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>“<mark>Nan tachradh</mark> i rium an-dràsta, <mark>chuireadh</mark> i na dh’fhuiling mi às mo chuimhne.”</strong><br/><small class="text-muted">“If I encountered her now, she would cause me to forget my suffering.” [#2 50]</small></li>
  <li><strong>“<mark>Nam b’</mark> e duine sam bith eile a bh’ ann, <mark>chanainn</mark> gur ann a Chaithris na h-Oidhche còmhla ri tè eile chaidh e.”</strong><br/><small class="text-muted">“If it were any other man, I would say that he had gone on ‘night-duty’ with another woman.” [#2 83]</small></li>
  <li><strong>“<mark>Bhiodh</mark> sinn fada nad chomain <mark>nan gleidheadh</mark> tu seo agad fhèin.”</strong><br/><small class="text-muted">“We would be greatly in your debt if you kept this to yourself.” [#2 68]</small></li>
  <li><strong>“<mark>Nan cuirinn</mark> mo bhràthair nam àite ...”</strong><br/><small class="text-muted">“If I sent my brother in my place ...” [#2 91]</small></li>
  <li><strong>“<mark>Nan sguireadh</mark> tu a phàigheadh sin, <mark>thigeadh</mark> e gu chiall.”</strong><br/><small class="text-muted">“If you stopped paying that [allowance], he would come to his senses.” [#2 7]</small></li>
  <li><strong>“<mark>Dè chanadh</mark> am baile <mark>nan cluinneadh</mark> iad gu robh d’ athair a’ ruagadh luch an dèidh dha comanachadh?”</strong><br/><small class="text-muted">“What would the town say if they heard that your father was chasing a mouse after taking communion” [#2 11]</small></li>
</ul>
<p>Here are some more canonical corpus examples from past-tense narrative:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Bha na mèirlich a’ smaoineachadh <mark>nan deigheadh</mark> iad dhachaigh gum <mark>biodh</mark> am poileasman aig an doras glè aithghearr.</strong><br/><small class="text-muted">‘The burglars were thinking if they went home that the policeman would be at the door very soon.’ [#2 53]</small></li>
  <li><strong><mark>Nam faigheadh</mark> e an obair <mark>nach dòcha</mark> gun deigheadh iad a dh’fhuireach sa bhaile mhòr.</strong><br/><small class="text-muted">‘If he got the job might they not go to live in the city.’ [#2 89]</small></li>
  <li><strong><mark>Dh’fheumadh</mark> iad an t-airgead <mark>nan deigheadh</mark> iad a Ghlaschu.</strong><br/><small class="text-muted">‘They would need the money if they were to go to Glasgow.’ [#2 89]</small></li>
  <li><strong>’S e crangaid a bha seo agus <mark>shlaodadh</mark> aon duine an t-eathar <mark>nan cumadh</mark> dithis eile na seasamh air a druim i.</strong><br/><small class="text-muted">‘This was a crank and one man would pull the boat if two others kept it upright.’ [#2 96]</small></li>
  <li><strong><mark>Nam fuiricheadh</mark> e gus an tigeadh athair, <mark>dh’fhaodadh</mark> e iasg a thoirt thuice cuideachd.</strong><br/> <small class="text-muted">‘If he waited until his father came, he would be able to take her a fish as well.’ [#2 123]</small></li>
</ul>
<p>In the following past-tense narrative example, <strong>nan</strong> is governed by a verbal noun rather than a conditional verb form:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Smaoinich Seòras air rocaid eile ullachadh airson a <mark>losgadh</mark> air an dithis a bha sa chèaban <mark>nan tigeadh</mark> iad a-mach.</strong><br/><small class="text-muted">‘George thought about preparing another rocket to fire at the pair in the cabin if they came out.’ [#2 100]</small></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>nan robh</strong> is often used as an alternative to <strong>nam biodh</strong>, as in the following past-tense narrative example</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong><mark>Nan robh</mark> e air fuireach san eilean an àite a dhachaigh a dhèanamh an Glaschu ...</strong><br/><small class="text-muted">‘If only he had stayed on the island instead of making his home in Glasgow ...’ [#2 60]</small></li>
</ul>
<p>You will find many examples involving non-canonical tense usage:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong><mark>Chuala</mark> mi fealla-dhà aige uair is uair, gu h-àraidh <mark>nam biodh</mark> misgear air a bheulaibh.</strong><br/><small class="text-muted">‘I heard him [the sheriff] joke occasionally especially if a drunkard was in front of him.’ [#2 73]</small></li>
  <li><strong>Ach <mark>thairg</mark> iad seo £300 <mark>nan tugadh</mark> e gu muir iad sa bhad.</strong><br/><small class="text-muted">‘But they offered £300 if he took them to sea immediately.’ [#2 98]</small></li>
  <li><strong>Bha fios agam o chionn fhada gu <mark>robh</mark> Iain air a bhith ainmeil mar phoileas-lorg <mark>nan robh</mark> e air an dreuchd sin a roghnachadh.</strong><br/><small class="text-muted">‘I had known for a long time that John would have been a famous detective if he had chosen that career.’ [#2 85]</small></li>
  <li><strong>Bha beachd aice gu <mark>robh</mark> Kevin air a murt <mark>nan robh</mark> i cho aosta ri Ailig.</strong><br/><small class="text-muted">‘She thought that Kevin would have killed her if she had been as old as Alec. [#2 110]</small></li>
</ul>

